To Tom Joynt:<br><br>
Hi!<br><br>
Meet a &quot;psychiatric&quot; casualty. I feel the term 'psychological casualty' is more appropriate as it permits latitude in one's view of the subject.<br><br>
You will find numerous postings on this site concerning PTSD (Post Traumatic Stress Disorder), some of which I authored in the course of several &quot;conversations&quot;. You may find material that adds to your understanding of the continuing psychological legacy of the Vietnam War. <br><br>
My personal experience is one of repression of memories of events that continue to be as haunting and as real as the moment of experience when they surface as flashbacks. There are physiological and personality manifestations that add a variety to the disorder one would sooner forget if forgetting were an option. Of course, I can't forget. All I can hope to achieve in time is a gradual conversion to just &quot;bad memories&quot;. <br><br>
I would be pleased to answer any questions you have on this subject.     
